DESeq analysis of Pasilla knock-downs

This guide follows the Bioconductor RNA-Seq workflow to find differentially expressed genes using DESeq2. Load the hciR package on Github to run the R code.

You can render this HTML report by finding the path to the DESeq.Rmd file in inst/Rmd.

library(hciR)
rmd <- system.file("Rmd", "DESeq.Rmd", package="hciR")
render(rmd,  output_dir=".")

Load samples and counts

Load the pasilla counts and samples and fix the file name to match column names in the count matrix.

setwd( system.file("extdata", package="pasilla") )
counts  <- read_tsv("pasilla_gene_counts.tsv" )
samples <- read_csv("pasilla_sample_annotation.csv")
samples$file <- gsub("fb$", "", samples$file )
samples

counts <- filter_counts(counts)

Run DESeq

Combine the counts and samples to create a DESeqDataSet object and calculate the regularized log transform (rlog) for sample visualizations.

dds <- deseq_from_tibble(counts, samples,  design = ~ condition)
#  Reordering columns in counts to match samples
#  estimating size factors
#  estimating dispersions
#  gene-wise dispersion estimates
#  mean-dispersion relationship
#  final dispersion estimates
#  fitting model and testing
rld <- r_log(dds)

PCA plot

Plot the first two principal components using the rlog values from the top 500 variable genes. You can hover over points to view sample names and type or zoom into groups of points in this interactive highchart.

plot_pca(rld, "condition", tooltip=c("file", "type") , width=700)

Cluster all the rlog values using the R function dist to calculate the Euclidean distance between samples.

plot_dist(rld , c("condition", "type"))

Gene annotations

Load fruitfly annotations from Ensembl.

fly <- read_biomart("fly")
#  Downloaded 19639 results, grouping into 17559 rows with a unique Ensembl ID

Result tables

Get the DESeq results using a 5% false discovery rate (FDR). This function will compare alll treatment combinations, which only includes one in this study.

res <- results_all(dds, fly, alpha= 0.05)
#  Using adjusted p-value < 0.05
#  
#  1. treated vs. untreated: 412 up and 438 down regulated
#  Note: 723 rows in results are missing from biomart table
datatable(top_genes(res)[, c(1:2, 4:7, 11)], options=list(pageLength=5) ) %>%
  formatRound(5:6, 2) %>% formatSignif(7,2)

Browse results

Create a flex dashboard using the top 1000 genes sorted by p-value in pasilla_flex.html. The MA-plot and volcano plot are linked, so you can click and drag to create a box to highlight points and then view matching rows in the table. You can also drag the box around the plot to easily highlight other points and rows. In addition, you can search for genes in the table using the search box, but need to click on the row in order to highlight the points in the plots. The sliders can also be used to limit the results.

rmd <- system.file("Rmd", "DESeq_flex.Rmd", package="hciR")
render(rmd, output_file="pasilla_flex.html",  output_dir=".",
         params=list( results= res, title = "Pasilla treated vs. untreated", top= 1000 ))

Save results

Save the DESeq results to a single Excel file in DESeq.xlsx. The write_deseq function will also output raw counts, rlog values, normalized counts, samples and fly annotations.

write_deseq( dds, res, rld, fly)

Plot heatmaps

Select the top 40 genes sorted by p-value and cluster the rlog differences, so values in the heatmap represent the amount a gene deviates in a specific sample from the gene’s average across all samples.


plot_genes( top_counts( res, rld), c("condition", "type") )


Plot the top 400 genes using an interactive d3heatmap. Click and drag over a region in the plot to zoom and better view gene labels.

plot_genes( top_counts( res, rld, top=400), output="d3", xaxis_font_size=12)
